# Electrolysis

Electrolysis cell:

![[Pasted image 20260624143437.png|200]]

#Concept
1. Electrolyte - Compound that is decomposed (Can be molten ionic compound / aqueous solution)
2. Electrode -  Carbon rods  (inert rod)or metal rods, to conduct electricity to and from electrolyte
3. Anode - Positive electrode
4. Cathode - Negative electrode

How does it works:
 - The battery provide electrical energy to both of the rod which provide the rod charges
 - Electron flow to the rod connected to the negative terminal of the cell (cathode), and hence it will attract the positively charged ions (cation)
 - Cations will receive electrons from cathode to undergo reduction
 - Electron flow from the rod connected to the positive terminal of the cell (anode), and hence it will attract the negatively charged ions (anion)
 - Anions will donate electrons to the anode to undergo oxidation

Electrolysis:
 - #Definition Decomposition of a compound into its element by an electric current
 - Carried out through electrolysis cell
 - During electrolysis, <mark style="background: #FF5582A6;">positive ions/cations</mark> move to <mark style="background: #FF5582A6;">cathode</mark> to gain electrons and <mark style="background: #ADCCFFA6;">negative ions</mark> move to <mark style="background: #ADCCFFA6;">anion</mark> to lose electrons

