### Quantitative electrolysis

Mass of a substance produced at an electrode during electrolysis is proportional to:
 - Time over which a constant electric current passes
 - Strength of the electric current

#Calculation 
To calculate amount of substances deposited,
- Calculate the charge produced in t time with current I, $Q = I \times t$
- Construct the half equations and find the charge of electrons to produces one mole of substance, $Q_{total} = n \times F, \text{where F is the Faraday's constant, } \ F = 96500 \ C^{-1}\  mol$ 
- Calculate amount of substances deposited, $x$ with Faraday's second law of electrolysis, $\frac{1}{x} = \frac{nF}{Q}$ 
- To calculate the Avogadro constant L, use $L = \frac{\text{charge on 1 mole of electrons}}{\text{charge of 1 electron}}$

