### Measuring Standard Electrode

![[Pasted image 20260624155815.png]]

1. Metal / metal ion half-cell (Example: $Cu^{2+} / Cu$)
$$
\begin{flalign*}\\
\text{Half equation: } \\
&Cu^{2+} \ (aq) \ + \ 2e^{-} \ \rightleftharpoons \ Cu \ (s) &&E^{\textordmasculine} = + \ 0.34 \ V\\
&H^{+} \ (aq) \ + \ e^{-} \ \rightleftharpoons \ \frac{1}{2}H_2 \ (g) &&E^{\textordmasculine} =   0.00 \ V \\
\end{flalign*}
$$
- #Concept Explanation
	-  The $Cu^{2+} / Cu$ half-cell is connected to a standard hydrogen electrode
	- A voltmeter is connected between the wire connecting both electrode to measure the $E^{\textordmasculine}$ value with the Cu rod is connected to the positive terminal of voltmeter
	- A salt bridge is connected between both electrolytes to allow flow of ions so that complete the circuit 
	- Wire is connected to the electrode to allow flow of electrons
	- Voltmeter shown a reading of +0.34V, which means the electrons flow from the positive terminal ($Cu^{2+} / Cu$) to the negative terminal ($H^{+}/H_2$).
	- Hence, $Cu^{2+}$ will accept electrons from the $H^{+}/H_2$ half-cell and $H_2$ will lose electrons to the $Cu^{2+} / Cu$ half-cell

```ad-note
Salt bridge normally either can be filter paper or $KNO_3$ or any other salt that will not undergo precipitation with the reactant.
```

