### Gibbs Free Energy and Cell Potential

#Calculation
The relationship of Gibbs free energy change and standard electrode potential can be shown as:
$$
\Updelta G^{\textordmasculine} = -nFE^{\textordmasculine}_{cell}
$$
where
- $\Updelta G^{\textordmasculine}$ is the standard Gibbs free energy in $J \ mol^{-1}$
- n is the number of moles of electrons transferred in the cell reaction
- F is the Faraday constant, $F = 96500 \ C \ mol^{-1}$
- $E^{\textordmasculine}_{cell}$ is the standard cell potential

#Concept 
The relationship of Gibbs free energy change, standard electrode potential and equilibrium coefficient also can be described:

| Standard cell potential, $E^{\textordmasculine}_{cell}$ | Gibbs free energy, $\Updelta G^{\textordmasculine}$ |                  Effects                   | Equilibrium coefficient, $K$ |
|:-------------------------------------------------------:|:---------------------------------------------------:|:------------------------------------------:|:----------------------------:|
|                            0                            |                          0                          |         Equation is in equilibrium         |              1               |
|                         > + 0.1                         |                  Slightly negative                  |        More products than reactants        |             > 1              |
|                         > + 0.6                         |                        << 0                         | Forward reaction is complete/irreversible  |              -               |
|                         < - 0.1                         |                  Slightly positive                  |        More reactants than products        |             < 1              |
|                         < - 0.6                         |                        >> 0                         | Backward reaction is complete/irreversible |              -               |
